orset/IMG_2642.jpg" alt=""> </a><div class="amazingcarousel-hover-effect" style="display:none;position:absolute;left:0;top:0;width:100%;height:100%;cursor:pointer;background-image:url('https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/slider/skins/hoveroverlay-64-64-6.png');background-repeat:no-repeat;background-position:center center;"></div></div><div class="amazingcarousel-title"></div></div></li><li class="amazingcarousel-item" style="display: block; position: relative; background-image: none; background-color: transparent; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; float: left; width: 150px;"><div class="amazingcarousel-item-container" style="position: relative; margin: 0px 2px;"><div class="amazingcarousel-image"> <a href="&#10;https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Front-Busk-Corset/IMG_2644.jpg" title="" class="html5lightbox" data-group="amazingcarousel"> <img src="&#10;https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Front-Busk-Corset/IMG_2644.jpg" alt=""> </a><div class="amazingcarousel-hover-effect" style="display:none;position:absolute;left:0;top:0;width:100%;height:100%;cursor:pointer;background-image:url('https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/slider/skins/hoveroverlay-64-64-6.png');background-repeat:no-repeat;background-position:center center;"></div></div><div class="amazingcarousel-title"></div></div></li><div style="clear:both;"></div></ul></div></div><div class="amazingcarousel-prev" style="overflow: hidden; position: absolute; cursor: pointer; width: 32px; height: 32px; background: url(&quot;https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/slider/skins/arrows-32-32-1.png&quot;) left top no-repeat; display: block;"></div><div class="amazingcarousel-next" style="overflow: hidden; position: absolute; cursor: pointer; width: 32px; height: 32px; background: url(&quot;https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/slider/skins/arrows-32-32-1.png&quot;) right top no-repeat; display: block;"></div></div></div></div></div><p><strong>Features:</strong></p><ul><li>Front busk corset;</li><li>A corset for a teenager body proportions;</li><li>Tiered skirt with ruffles.</li></ul><p><strong>Skills you gain:</strong></p><ul><li>How to sew a teens corset with a steel busk;</li><li>How to customize a standard corset pattern to make it suitable for a teenage girl;</li><li>How to&nbsp;make a perfect skirt with many ruffles;</li><li>Original corset decorations.</li></ul><p><strong>Where to use:</strong></p><ul><li>An exclusive fancy dress for&nbsp;your teenage child;</li><li>Perfect solution for proms, celebrations, costume parties and other special events.</li></ul><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;4h 23m</p></div></div><div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript"><div class="overlay"></div><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"> <span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"> <span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"> </span><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"> </span> <span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"> <span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"> </span><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"> </span><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-16-making-calculations/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-16-making-calculations/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-08-08T21:00:25+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-08-08T21:00:42+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 16. Making Calculations."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 16. Making Calculations."><meta itemprop="description" content="To cut the skirt, I need to first calculate the ratio and then divide the total length between separate tiers and figure out fabric consumption."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Corset with a Front Busk for 15 Years Old Girl"><meta itemprop="keywords" content="corset with a front busk for 15 years old girl, video"> <span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"> </span><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 16. Making Calculations.</h1><p><strong>To cut the skirt, I need to first calculate the ratio and then divide the total length between separate tiers and figure out fabric consumption. </strong></p><p>It will be a tiered skirt with ruffles. The skirt will be made of separate strips of fabric with ruffles sewn in-between them. Preliminary calculations are the only challenging moment because the sewing process is easy as long as you get it right with the calculations and the lengths and widths of all fabric strips. The rest is a matter of skills: you simply assemble the skirt by joining the pieces one by one.</p><p><strong>It is a lot easier to assemble a skirt from separate tiers with ruffles in-between than sew separately cut ruffles on a ready full sweep skirt.</strong> Firstly, it is very hard to maintain the same intervals between the ruffles when sewing them on a full sweep skirt. Secondly, you will have to find a way to hide the raw edge of the ruffles. Thirdly, I believe that a regular full sweep skirt does not look as full and does not cascade down as beautifully. In other words, I prefer making such skirts tiered. As I said before, the only challenge deals with those preliminary calculations. Joining tiers and ruffles one by one is as easy as pie.</p><p><strong>The best ratio for a garment like ours is 1:1. </strong>It is always a winner. The corset is mono-coloured and the skirt is somewhat bright. I have chosen fabric with thin blue stripes which, from a distance, looks like plain light blue fabric with ripples. It is a classic nautical theme, a very lovely combination of colours.</p><p><strong>Since we are using the 1:1 ratio, the visible part of the skirt should have the same length as the corset. </strong>&nbsp;Take the finished corset, put it face side down, and measure it in a straight line from the top edge to the bottom edge.</p><p><strong>I got 29-30cm, which means that the visible part of the skirt should also be 29-30cm long.</strong> Modern teenage girls don't like when skirts or pants sit right at their natural waist. They like it when the waist is lowered by at least some 2cm. I will account for this in the calculations: if the distance from the waist to the bottom edge of the corset is 12cm, then the invisible part of the skirt (yoke and waistband) will be 10cm.</p><p><strong>The first ruffle is supposed to show right from under the corset.</strong> The yoke and the waistband will stay underneath the corset while the first ruffle will run along its bottom edge.</p><p><strong>The total length of all tiers is 29cm.</strong> I divide it in two 12cm long tiers and another ruffle tier of 5cm.</p><p><strong>Each 12cm long tier will be made of three fabric strips with a width of 4cm when finished. </strong>The ruffle should be at least 1cm wider than the background. Therefore, if the ready background strip has a width of 4cm, then a ready ruffle should have a width of 5cm. Considering all this, I will make the last tier 5cm.</p><p><strong>Let us do the maths. I have drawn a table to make things clear.&nbsp; </strong></p><p><strong><br> <img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Front-Busk-Corset/transcritps/Tutorial%2016.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Let us start from the top. </strong></p><p><strong>The hidden part of the skirt is 10cm. </strong>It is made of a yoke and a waistband. The waistband is quite standard and has a width of 3.5cm. Its fabric consumption is calculated by multiplying 3.5cm by two, which makes 7cm, and adding another 2.5cm for the seam allowances, which makes a total of 9.5cm.</p><p>The required width of the background fabric strips is recorded <strong>in the first column of the table titled "Bckgr. Width." </strong>The first value is the width of a finished strip and the width of a full cut strip is given in brackets.</p><p>In other words, 3.5cm is the width of a ready waistband and 9.5cm is the width of a fabric strip it is made of.</p><p><strong>I subtract 3.5cm from 10cm and get 6.5cm for the yoke.</strong> I add another 2.5cm for the seam allowances and get a fabric strip with a width of 9cm (for cutting the yoke).</p><p><strong>All other strips are supposed to be cut with a width of 6.5cm (seam allowances included) and have a width of 4cm when finished.&nbsp; </strong></p><p><strong>The second column titled "Bckgr. Length" contains the lengths of all fabric strips which form the background for sewing on the ruffles.</strong></p><p><strong>Waistband Length:</strong> Olga's waist circumference is 64cm, which is enough for the waistband, plus I need to add another 5cm for a closure flap.</p><p><strong>Yoke Length: </strong>Olga's stomach circumference measured 14cm below the waist is 87cm. I will make it 90cm including the seam allowances and the closure. This means the length of the skirt should be 90cm at this level.</p><p><strong>The first strip (or the first tier) will be sewn to the yoke. </strong>This tier is made of three background strips with a width of 4cm each and with ruffles sewn in-between. <strong>What does this mean? </strong>The first background strip must be two times longer than the yoke in order to start forming the flare of the skirt. In other words, it must be 180cm long. <strong>All these strips must have the same length, i.e. 180cm.</strong></p><p><strong>What will vary is the length of ruffles.</strong> The first ruffle strip must have the same length as the background strip it will be sewn to because they will be gathered simultaneously after getting joined. In other words, both the first background strip and the first ruffle will be gathered down to half their original length.</p><p>The widths of ruffles are recorded <strong>in the third column titled "Ruffle Width."</strong> All ruffles will have the same width. As I said before, it will be 5cm when finished. But each ruffle is a fabric strip folded in half, and, therefore, 5cm plus 5cm makes 10cm plus 2.5cm for seam allowances. I will cut them with a width of 13cm instead of 12.5cm because the fabric tends to fray a little and that 0.5cm will disappear anyway.&nbsp; Summing it up, all ruffles will be cut as 13cm wide strips.</p><p><strong>The fourth column, "Ruffle Length," contains the lengths of all ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>The second ruffle of the first tier </strong>must be two times longer than the background to form beautiful folds because I will not gather the fabric when joining the separate parts of the tier. All those three background strips with a width of 4cm will be sewn together without gathering. You should only gather when joining it with the yoke. <strong>Since the length of the first ruffle is 180cm, then the other two ruffles must be two times longer, i.e. 360cm each.&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong></p><p><strong>Let us figure out the lengths of the strips used for the second tier.</strong> It has a width of 12cm and is made of three separate strips just like the first one. This tier must be two times longer than the previous one to create the flare effect. In other words, it must be 360cm and not 180cm. Both the background strip and the ruffle strip must have a length of 360cm because they will be sewn together and then gathered and joined with the first tier. While both of these strips will be 360cm long, the ruffle sewn to the next background strip will be two times longer, i.e. 720cm. The third ruffle will also be 720cm long but the length of the background will not change, i.e. the ruffle will be gathered down to half its original length and sewn to a 360cm long background strip.</p><p><strong>The last tier</strong> is a ruffle with a width of 5cm. Again, I need to cut a 720cm long strip and gather it down to 360cm to form a beautiful neat ruffle.</p><p>I hope this does not sound too confusing. The calculations are included in the file with the pattern adjustments table where you will find Olga's measurements, pattern measurements, and all adjustment values. The key point is that each subsequent tier is supposed to be two times longer than the previous one; and each tier is made of three strips of fabric with ruffles sewn in-between. And the ruffle is always cut two times longer than the background it is sewn to. As long as you understand this, you will know how to calculate any tiered skirt.</p><p><strong>Let us figure out fabric consumption. </strong></p><p><strong>I start from the total length of all fabric strips used for the background and cut with a width of 6.5cm (4cm when finished). </strong>Let us look at the table: there are three 180cm long strips and three 360cm long strips, which <strong>makes a total length of 1,620cm.</strong> If you divide this total length by the width of your fabric, you will know how many strips you need to prepare. Suppose my fabric has a width of 150cm. I divide 1,620cm by 150cm and get 11 strips with a width of 6.5cm.</p><p><strong>This tells us the following about fabric consumption: </strong></p><p><strong>6.5cm x 11 strips ≈ 70cm = 0.7m (considering that the fabric has a width of 150cm).</strong></p><p><strong>Next, I find the total length of all ruffle strips cut with a width of 13cm. </strong>According to the table, there is one 180cm long strip, three 360cm long strips, and three 720cm long strips, which <strong>makes a total length of 3,420cm.</strong> I divide it by the width of my fabric (150cm) and get about 23 strips.</p><p><strong>And, therefore, </strong></p><p><strong>13m x 23 strips ≈ 300cm = 3m (considering that the fabric has a width of 150cm). </strong></p><p><strong>I will add another 20cm to account for the waistband and the yoke. </strong></p><p><strong>Total fabric consumption is as follows: </strong></p><p><strong>0.7m + 3m + 0.2m = 3.9m ≈ 4m. </strong></p><p><strong>You can take 4.2m just to be on the safe side. </strong></p></div></div></div><div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern"><p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p> <a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Front-Busk-Corset/patterns/FrontBuskCorset.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://cdn.shortpixel.ai/client/q_glossy,ret_img/https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Front Busk Corset Pattern</a><br></div><div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="diploma"><div class="dark-get-started margin-0"><p>In order to receive the Corset Academy graduation diploma you need to submit your graduation work.<br> Upload the photo of the garment that you made after completing the course.<br> I will personally review your work.<br> After the approval you will receive a personalized diploma to your email box, no longer than within 1 business day.</p><p class="text-right">Tatiana Kozorovitsky.</p><form id="diplomaForm"><h4>Your datails:</h4><div class="form-group"> <input type="text" id="firstname" class="form-control" placeholder="Enter first name" required=""><p class="firstname error">Enter your first name</p></div><div class="form-group"> <input type="text" id="lastname" class="form-control" placeholder="Enter last name" required=""><p class="lastname error">Enter your last name</p></div><h4>Choose a course:</h4><div class="radio"> <input type="radio" name="course" id="option1" value="1"> <label for="option1"> <em>Wedding gowns design and sewing course.</em> </label></div><div class="radio"> <input type="radio" name="course" id="option2" value="2"> <label for="option2"> <em>Evening dresses design and sewing course.</em> </label></div><div class="radio"> <input type="radio" name="course" id="option3" value="3"> <label for="option3"> <em>Corsetry design and sewing course.</em> </label></div><p class="course error margin-10-bottom">Select course</p><div class="form-group"> <label class="uploadbutton"><div class="button">Choose file</div><div class="pull-left"><div class="input">No file selected</div></div> <input type="file" id="fileupload" name="files[]" data-url="https://corsetacademy